Then, too, no difficulty is presented by the fact that goods seized by pirates do not become their property; because this is true only of pirates who are not ene- mies‚ and not of pirates who are likewise enemies. These pirates are enemies‚ as I say, and the Turk along with them is an enemy of the Venetians, since he protects those pirates openly everywhere and always. But if the goods were certainly lost to the Venetians, what grounds for displeasure have they, if Englishmen bought them? 00 Cannot each individual advantage himself while he is not injuring others? Or is the Kingdom of England not free? pp The Venetians, in answer to the complaint of the French King that gunpowder had been bought at Venice and carried to his enemies‚ asserted that their state was free and that no one was ever forbidden to trade there. Ι likewise declare that my Englishmen are free and have not been forbidden to trade anywhere. qq To secure what does not injure you and advantages the other man should be the judge's continual aim, and even the devil should get his due, as our countrymen say.
